Right of withdrawal If you're an EEA-based consumer, your contract with Kaggle is by law subject to an automatic right of withdrawal for 14 days from the date of the conclusion of the contract. To exercise the right of withdrawal, you must inform us of your decision to withdraw from this contract by an unequivocal statement (eg a letter sent by post or an e-mail). Corps : *Ready to enter the first e-sport event where YOU create your OWN cards?* Hello everyone, We, as Pre-Ing2 students, have made our own *multiplayer video game* and invite you to *our competitive event!* *Using your phone*, you'll be able to play a *card game inspired by Hearthstone and Yu-Gi-Oh* where you'll first *create your cards* and *unleash your creativity*: come up with a *card name*, draw a *picture*, adjust the *stats*, add powerful *card effects*... Corps : zoom is from the email 8 feb Link to Zoom: Melanie Shi is inviting you to a scheduled Zoom meeting. Topic: Melanie Shi's Personal Meeting Room Join Zoom Meeting https://us05web.zoom.us/j/4498398013?pwd=CKBWYwKqickg9Lboe2IjllS1CU472F.1 Meeting ID: 449 839 8013 Passcode: V1x11k On Thu, Mar 7, 2024 at 11:57 AM MÃ©lanie Shi wrote: > Dear all, > > It is Melanie here â€” I am really sorry about missing todayâ€™s courses with > prior notice but Iâ€™ve just returned from Hong Kong and I am simultaneously > jet lagged and I have contracted an infection on one of my legs that has > made it very painful for me to walk and I just could not go so far for the > course. I hope everyoneâ€™s break was okay. > > Since the semester terminates around 8 April we should go ahead with the > presentations. I was going to check in as to who has had time to do this so > far â€” there were a couple questions that arose after the last session where > students asked if they could present in groups â€” by pairs of two, this is > alright with me â€” and others who emailed over the vacation to ask for > clarification on the assignment. Thus, to clarify: please prepare a 5-7 > presentation with powerpoint support or article(s) for the next course, > presenting research on a company that interests you or an industry and > giving a summary of the state of affairs; or on AI from which you can draw > on the articles we have read so far. It will count for a short note. Try > and draw on reputable news sources like the ones we have been reading > (Economist, Financial Times, Le Monde, LMD, studies from Polytechnique, > Sciences Po, Politico, CNRS, sources in English, as well as magazines and > reports that specialise in the industry of your choice - you can find this > on google). > > The plan for the course, otherwise, was to talk about the opening of the > new microsoft partnership in AI in France (in the news two days ago, see > below) and more think pieces about humanity and AI, as well as some > articles touching on new aspects of the tech race between the US and China, > and an update on Space X. > > The longer analysis touches on governance of AI in Europe vs. China and > again in US vs. China. > > > > Dear all, > Class #2 : please prepare a 5-7 presentation with powerpoint support or > article(s) for the next course, presenting research on a company that > interests you or an industry and giving a summary of the state of affairs; > or on AI from which you can draw on the articles we have read so far. It > will count for a short note. If there are any remaining questions we can > clarify this more in the next session, but I think that we should get > started on this project and the oral presentations, I believe that 8 April > is the last session for the course. > > > Here are some more articles to read around the AI issue that weâ€™ll talk > about more the next class > AI and democracy : > https://www.forbes.com/sites/neilsahota/2024/02/02/ai-and-the-shadow-over-democracy-the-rising-threat-to-global-elections/?sh=5b9458ab657b > > Are artificial intelligence and human intelligence comparable? - a study > by the Institut Polytechnique of Paris > > https://www.polytechnique-insights.com/en/columns/science/are-artificial-intelligence-and-human-intelligence-comparable/ > > Key takeaways > > - Artificial intelligence and human intelligence are inevitably > compared. > - This confrontation is intrinsic to the history of AI: some > approaches are inspired by human cognition, while others are completely > independent from it. > - The imprecise and controversial definition of intelligence makes > this comparison vague. > - Consciousness remains one of the main elements that AI seems to lack > in order to imitate human intelligence. > - The question of comparison in fact raises ethical issues about the > use, purpose and regulation of AI. > > â€œThe ways AI will change the future of workâ€ > > https://www.polytechnique-insights.com/en/columns/digital/artificial-intelligence-what-impact-will-it-have-on-work-in-the-future/ > > 75 million jobs could be automated > > Although the potential for change is much greater than automation, the > risk remains very real, with 2.3% of jobs worldwide affected. > Administrative jobs would be heavily impacted by automation. â€œCall centre > employees, secretaries, data entry operators â€“ simple, linear activities > with little variation in tasks and little interaction with others â€“ could > be replaced by bots,â€ explains Janine Berg. In recent years, office workers > have already seen their day-to-day work evolve. According to the experts, > 24% of their tasks are highly exposed to AI, and 58% are moderately > exposed. This is by far the occupation most at risk. This means that 2.3% > of jobs worldwide, or 75 million, could end up being automated. > > The economist details a number of actions that governments need to take: > â€œreflecting on the question of the balance of power, the voice of workers > affected by labour market adjustments, respect for existing standards and > rights, and the appropriate use of national social protections, as well as > training systems will be crucial elements in steering the deployment of AI > in the world of work.â€ > > Here are some videos also that touch on this subject > > https://www.ted.com/talks/richard_socher_why_ai_is_humanity_s_mirror_and_what_we_can_learn_from_it > > > https://hbr.org/podcast/2024/02/the-science-of-making-truthful-ai?ab=HP-hero-latest-text-3 > > Objet : Re: State of the union on Silicon Valley
Corps : Dear all, It is Melanie here â€” I am really sorry about missing todayâ€™s courses with prior notice but Iâ€™ve just returned from Hong Kong and I am simultaneously jet lagged and I have contracted an infection on one of my legs that has made it very painful for me to walk and I just could not go so far for the course. I hope everyoneâ€™s break was okay. Since the semester terminates around 8 April we should go ahead with the presentations. I was going to check in as to who has had time to do this so far â€” there were a couple questions that arose after the last session where students asked if they could present in groups â€” by pairs of two, this is alright with me â€” and others who emailed over the vacation to ask for clarification on the assignment. Thus, to clarify: please prepare a 5-7 presentation with powerpoint support or article(s) for the next course, presenting research on a company that interests you or an industry and giving a summary of the state of affairs; or on AI from which you can draw on the articles we have read so far. It will count for a short note. Try and draw on reputable news sources like the ones we have been reading (Economist, Financial Times, Le Monde, LMD, studies from Polytechnique, Sciences Po, Politico, CNRS, sources in English, as well as magazines and reports that specialise in the industry of your choice - you can find this on google). The plan for the course, otherwise, was to talk about the opening of the new microsoft partnership in AI in France (in the news two days ago, see below) and more think pieces about humanity and AI, as well as some articles touching on new aspects of the tech race between the US and China, and an update on Space X. The longer analysis touches on governance of AI in Europe vs. China and again in US vs. China. Dear all, Class #2 : please prepare a 5-7 presentation with powerpoint support or article(s) for the next course, presenting research on a company that interests you or an industry and giving a summary of the state of affairs; or on AI from which you can draw on the articles we have read so far. It will count for a short note. If there are any remaining questions we can clarify this more in the next session, but I think that we should get started on this project and the oral presentations, I believe that 8 April is the last session for the course. Here are some more articles to read around the AI issue that weâ€™ll talk about more the next class AI and democracy : https://www.forbes.com/sites/neilsahota/2024/02/02/ai-and-the-shadow-over-democracy-the-rising-threat-to-global-elections/?sh=5b9458ab657b Are artificial intelligence and human intelligence comparable? - a study by the Institut Polytechnique of Paris https://www.polytechnique-insights.com/en/columns/science/are-artificial-intelligence-and-human-intelligence-comparable/ Key takeaways - Artificial intelligence and human intelligence are inevitably compared. - This confrontation is intrinsic to the history of AI: some approaches are inspired by human cognition, while others are completely independent from it. - The imprecise and controversial definition of intelligence makes this comparison vague. - Consciousness remains one of the main elements that AI seems to lack in order to imitate human intelligence. - The question of comparison in fact raises ethical issues about the use, purpose and regulation of AI. â€œThe ways AI will change the future of workâ€ https://www.polytechnique-insights.com/en/columns/digital/artificial-intelligence-what-impact-will-it-have-on-work-in-the-future/ 75 million jobs could be automated Although the potential for change is much greater than automation, the risk remains very real, with 2.3% of jobs worldwide affected. Administrative jobs would be heavily impacted by automation. â€œCall centre employees, secretaries, data entry operators â€“ simple, linear activities with little variation in tasks and little interaction with others â€“ could be replaced by bots,â€ explains Janine Berg. In recent years, office workers have already seen their day-to-day work evolve. According to the experts, 24% of their tasks are highly exposed to AI, and 58% are moderately exposed. This is by far the occupation most at risk. This means that 2.3% of jobs worldwide, or 75 million, could end up being automated. The economist details a number of actions that governments need to take: â€œreflecting on the question of the balance of power, the voice of workers affected by labour market adjustments, respect for existing standards and rights, and the appropriate use of national social protections, as well as training systems will be crucial elements in steering the deployment of AI in the world of work.â€ Here are some videos also that touch on this subject https://www.ted.com/talks/richard_socher_why_ai_is_humanity_s_mirror_and_what_we_can_learn_from_it https://hbr.org/podcast/2024/02/the-science-of-making-truthful-ai?ab=HP-hero-latest-text-3 Interesting Paris-based project on / using AI https://www.telecom-paris.fr/en/research/strategic-focuses/data-science-artificial-intelligence Geopolitical implications of AI and digital surveillance adoption (touching on the case of China) https://www.brookings.edu/articles/geopolitical-implications-of-ai-and-digital-surveillance-adoption/ China vs. USA â€œtech raceâ€ â€” we can focus on this issue as it is very interesting https://www-ft-com.ezproxy.depaul.edu/content/ef157204-a204-4512-8c50-fe60e166b41e https://www.reuters.com/technology/china-aims-boost-chip-production-despite-us-restrictions-ft-2024-02-06/#:~:text=Feb%206%20(Reuters)%20%2D%20Chinese,Financial%20Times%20reported%20on%20Tuesday https://www.polytechnique-insights.com/en/braincamps/economy/the-technology-war-between-china-and-the-usa/china-and-the-race-for-technological-supremacy/ https://www.polytechnique-insights.com/en/braincamps/economy/the-technology-war-between-china-and-the-usa/semiconductors-at-the-heart-of-the-china-us-rivalry/ Europe overtakes US as biggest artificial intelligence research partner with China https://sciencebusiness.net/news-byte/ai/europe-overtakes-us-biggest-artificial-intelligence-research-partner-china Article about the Silicon Valley Bank crash that occurred last year https://www.techtarget.com/whatis/feature/Silicon-Valley-Bank-collapse-explained-What-you-need-to-know Articles recently about Elon Musk who is also utilising AI (he created a company called an AI company called xAI) https://edition.cnn.com/2024/01/30/investing/elon-musk-pay-package-thrown-out/index.html Musk vs. Chinese electric cars https://cleantechnica.com/2024/02/07/elon-musk-super-bullish-on-chinese-electric-car-companies/ Europe is getting more and more of these options, while the US is still basically barren when it comes to Chinese EV options. Many other markets â€” like Chile , as an example â€” are somewhere in between. Thank you, hope this weather improves soon. MS *** Finally, here is preliminarily a link to my Zoom room. We will make up the class / any classes missed via zoomâ€¦ Potentially we can try to do this Wednesday (14 Fev) or perhaps the day of the course, Thursday (16 Fev). If not, we can hold an extra session over Zoom after the vacation (Week of 26 Fev). I will write to you to see how you are feeling about this. For those of you for whom itâ€™s possible (particularly the first course), can even do it tomorrow if thereâ€™s a time that works for you. If so, write me. It will count for a short note. If there are any remaining questions we can clarify this more in the next session, but I think that we should get started on this project and the oral presentations, I believe that 8 April is the last session for the course. Here are some more articles to read around the AI issue that weâ€™ll talk about more the next class AI and democracy : https://www.forbes.com/sites/neilsahota/2024/02/02/ai-and-the-shadow-over-democracy-the-rising-threat-to-global-elections/?sh=5b9458ab657b Are artificial intelligence and human intelligence comparable? - a study by the Institut Polytechnique of Paris https://www.polytechnique-insights.com/en/columns/science/are-artificial-intelligence-and-human-intelligence-comparable/ Key takeaways - Artificial intelligence and human intelligence are inevitably compared. - This confrontation is intrinsic to the history of AI: some approaches are inspired by human cognition, while others are completely independent from it. - The imprecise and controversial definition of intelligence makes this comparison vague. - Consciousness remains one of the main elements that AI seems to lack in order to imitate human intelligence. - The question of comparison in fact raises ethical issues about the use, purpose and regulation of AI. â€œThe ways AI will change the future of workâ€ https://www.polytechnique-insights.com/en/columns/digital/artificial-intelligence-what-impact-will-it-have-on-work-in-the-future/ 75 million jobs could be automated Although the potential for change is much greater than automation, the risk remains very real, with 2.3% of jobs worldwide affected. Administrative jobs would be heavily impacted by automation. â€œCall centre employees, secretaries, data entry operators â€“ simple, linear activities with little variation in tasks and little interaction with others â€“ could be replaced by bots,â€ explains Janine Berg. In recent years, office workers have already seen their day-to-day work evolve. According to the experts, 24% of their tasks are highly exposed to AI, and 58% are moderately exposed. This is by far the occupation most at risk. This means that 2.3% of jobs worldwide, or 75 million, could end up being automated. The economist details a number of actions that governments need to take: â€œreflecting on the question of the balance of power, the voice of workers affected by labour market adjustments, respect for existing standards and rights, and the appropriate use of national social protections, as well as training systems will be crucial elements in steering the deployment of AI in the world of work.â€ Here are some videos also that touch on this subject https://www.ted.com/talks/richard_socher_why_ai_is_humanity_s_mirror_and_what_we_can_learn_from_it https://hbr.org/podcast/2024/02/the-science-of-making-truthful-ai?ab=HP-hero-latest-text-3 Interesting Paris-based project on / using AI company called an AI company called xAI) https://edition.cnn.com/2024/01/30/investing/elon-musk-pay-package-thrown-out/index.html Musk vs. Chinese electric cars https://cleantechnica.com/2024/02/07/elon-musk-super-bullish-on-chinese-electric-car-companies/ Europe is getting more and more of these options, while the US is still basically barren when it comes to Chinese EV options. In any case, you can also keep reading about the debate over the technologization of labor which takes on more of a moral as well as an economic implication (see the first two articles)â€¦ and the following https://www.ben-evans.com/benedictevans/2023/7/2/working-with-ai https://www.brookings.edu/articles/understanding-the-impact-of-automation-on-workers-jobs-and-wages/ "So we must ask: Is this time really different? Objet : Re: State of the union on Silicon Valley
Corps : Dear all, It is Melanie here â€” I am really sorry about missing todayâ€™s courses with prior notice but Iâ€™ve just returned from Hong Kong and I am simultaneously jet lagged and I have contracted an infection on one of my legs that has made it very painful for me to walk and I just could not go so far for the course. I hope everyoneâ€™s break was okay. Since the semester terminates around 8 April we should go ahead with the presentations. I was going to check in as to who has had time to do this so far â€” there were a couple questions that arose after the last session where students asked if they could present in groups â€” by pairs of two, this is alright with me â€” and others who emailed over the vacation to ask for clarification on the assignment. Thus, to clarify: please prepare a 5-7 presentation with powerpoint support or article(s) for the next course, presenting research on a company that interests you or an industry and giving a summary of the state of affairs; or on AI from which you can draw on the articles we have read so far. It will count for a short note. Try and draw on reputable news sources like the ones we have been reading (Economist, Financial Times, Le Monde, LMD, studies from Polytechnique, Sciences Po, Politico, CNRS, sources in English, as well as magazines and reports that specialise in the industry of your choice - you can find this on google). The plan for the course, otherwise, was to talk about the opening of the new microsoft partnership in AI in France (in the news two days ago, see below) and more think pieces about humanity and AI, as well as some articles touching on new aspects of the tech race between the US and China, and an update on Space X. https://www.ft.com/technology The longer analysis touches on governance of AI in Europe vs. China and again in US vs. China. So, to prepare for the next week, letâ€™s have you work on your presentations (you can make a ppt with visual supports). I donâ€™t know about the projector in the classroom - you can always print copies or a visual support if this would work for you - but weâ€™ll find a solution. Take care Melanie >> Dear all, >> Class #2 : please prepare a 5-7 presentation with powerpoint support or article(s) for the next course, presenting research on a company that interests you or an industry and giving a summary of the state of affairs; or on AI from which you can draw on the articles we have read so far. It will count for a short note. If there are any remaining questions we can clarify this more in the next session, but I think that we should get started on this project and the oral presentations, I believe that 8 April is the last session for the course. >> >> >> Here are some more articles to read around the AI issue that weâ€™ll talk about more the next class >> AI and democracy : https://www.forbes.com/sites/neilsahota/2024/02/02/ai-and-the-shadow-over-democracy-the-rising-threat-to-global-elections/?sh=5b9458ab657b >> >> Are artificial intelligence and human intelligence comparable? - a study by the Institut Polytechnique of Paris >> https://www.polytechnique-insights.com/en/columns/science/are-artificial-intelligence-and-human-intelligence-comparable/ >> Key takeaways >> Artificial intelligence and human intelligence are inevitably compared. >> This confrontation is intrinsic to the history of AI: some approaches are inspired by human cognition, while others are completely independent from it. >> The imprecise and controversial definition of intelligence makes this comparison vague. >> Consciousness remains one of the main elements that AI seems to lack in order to imitate human intelligence. >> The question of comparison in fact raises ethical issues about the use, purpose and regulation of AI. >> â€œThe ways AI will change the future of workâ€ >> https://www.polytechnique-insights.com/en/columns/digital/artificial-intelligence-what-impact-will-it-have-on-work-in-the-future/ >> >> 75 million jobs could be automated >> >> Although the potential for change is much greater than automation, the risk remains very real, with 2.3% of jobs worldwide affected. Administrative jobs would be heavily impacted by automation. â€œCall centre employees, secretaries, data entry operators â€“ simple, linear activities with little variation in tasks and little interaction with others â€“ could be replaced by bots,â€ explains Janine Berg. In recent years, office workers have already seen their day-to-day work evolve. According to the experts, 24% of their tasks are highly exposed to AI, and 58% are moderately exposed. This is by far the occupation most at risk. This means that 2.3% of jobs worldwide, or 75 million, could end up being automated. >> >> >> The economist details a number of actions that governments need to take: â€œreflecting on the question of Objet : Re: State of the union on Silicon Valley
Corps : 2nd think piece on AI > On 15 Feb 2024, at 20:30, Melanie Shi wrote: > > Hi, > Some reading for the break > > > > >> On 8 Feb 2024, at 16:36, Melanie Shi > wrote: >> >> Dear all, >> Class #2 : please prepare a 5-7 presentation with powerpoint support or article(s) for the next course, presenting research on a company that interests you or an industry and giving a summary of the state of affairs; or on AI from which you can draw on the articles we have read so far. It will count for a short note. If there are any remaining questions we can clarify this more in the next session, but I think that we should get started on this project and the oral presentations, I believe that 8 April is the last session for the course. >> >> >> Here are some more articles to read around the AI issue that weâ€™ll talk about more the next class >> AI and democracy : https://www.forbes.com/sites/neilsahota/2024/02/02/ai-and-the-shadow-over-democracy-the-rising-threat-to-global-elections/?sh=5b9458ab657b >> >> Are artificial intelligence and human intelligence comparable? - a study by the Institut Polytechnique of Paris >> https://www.polytechnique-insights.com/en/columns/science/are-artificial-intelligence-and-human-intelligence-comparable/ >> Key takeaways >> Artificial intelligence and human intelligence are inevitably compared. >> This confrontation is intrinsic to the history of AI: some approaches are inspired by human cognition, while others are completely independent from it. >> The imprecise and controversial definition of intelligence makes this comparison vague. >> Consciousness remains one of the main elements that AI seems to lack in order to imitate human intelligence. >> The question of comparison in fact raises ethical issues about the use, purpose and regulation of AI. >> â€œThe ways AI will change the future of workâ€ >> https://www.polytechnique-insights.com/en/columns/digital/artificial-intelligence-what-impact-will-it-have-on-work-in-the-future/ >> >> 75 million jobs could be automated >> >> Although the potential for change is much greater than automation, the risk remains very real, with 2.3% of jobs worldwide affected. Administrative jobs would be heavily impacted by automation. â€œCall centre employees, secretaries, data entry operators â€“ simple, linear activities with little variation in tasks and little interaction with others â€“ could be replaced by bots,â€ explains Janine Berg. In recent years, office workers have already seen their day-to-day work evolve. According to the experts, 24% of their tasks are highly exposed to AI, and 58% are moderately exposed. This is by far the occupation most at risk. This means that 2.3% of jobs worldwide, or 75 million, could end up being automated. >> >> >> The economist details a number of actions that governments need to take: â€œreflecting on the question of the balance of power, the voice of workers affected by labour market adjustments, respect for existing standards and rights, and the appropriate use of national social protections, as well as training systems will be crucial elements in steering the deployment of AI in the world of work.â€ >> >> Here are some videos also that touch on this subject >> https://www.ted.com/talks/richard_socher_why_ai_is_humanity_s_mirror_and_what_we_can_learn_from_it >> https://hbr.org/podcast/2024/02/the-science-of-making-truthful-ai?ab=HP-hero-latest-text-3 >> >> Interesting Paris-based project on / using AI >> https://www.telecom-paris.fr/en/research/strategic-focuses/data-science-artificial-intelligence >> >> Geopolitical implications of AI and digital surveillance adoption (touching on the case of China) >> https://www.brookings.edu/articles/geopolitical-implications-of-ai-and-digital-surveillance-adoption/ >> >> China vs. USA â€œtech raceâ€ â€” we can focus on this issue as it is very interesting >> https://www-ft-com.ezproxy.depaul.edu/content/ef157204-a204-4512-8c50-fe60e166b41e >> >> https://www.reuters.com/technology/china-aims-boost-chip-production-despite-us-restrictions-ft-2024-02-06/#:~:text=Feb%206%20(Reuters)%20%2D%20Chinese,Financial%20Times%20reported%20on%20Tuesday >> >> https://www.polytechnique-insights.com/en/braincamps/economy/the-technology-war-between-china-and-the-usa/china-and-the-race-for-technological-supremacy/ >> >> https://www.polytechnique-insights.com/en/braincamps/economy/the-technology-war-between-china-and-the-usa/semiconductors-at-the-heart-of-the-china-us-rivalry/ >> >> Europe overtakes US as biggest text:
Objet : Re: State of the union on Silicon Valley
Corps : Dear all, Class #2 : please prepare a 5-7 presentation with powerpoint support or article(s) for the next course, presenting research on a company that interests you or an industry and giving a summary of the state of affairs; or on AI from which you can draw on the articles we have read so far. It will count for a short note. If there are any remaining questions we can clarify this more in the next session, but I think that we should get started on this project and the oral presentations, I believe that 8 April is the last session for the course. Here are some more articles to read around the AI issue that weâ€™ll talk about more the next class AI and democracy : https://www.forbes.com/sites/neilsahota/2024/02/02/ai-and-the-shadow-over-democracy-the-rising-threat-to-global-elections/?sh=5b9458ab657b Are artificial intelligence and human intelligence comparable? - a study by the Institut Polytechnique of Paris https://www.polytechnique-insights.com/en/columns/science/are-artificial-intelligence-and-human-intelligence-comparable/ Key takeaways Artificial intelligence and human intelligence are inevitably compared. This confrontation is intrinsic to the history of AI: some approaches are inspired by human cognition, while others are completely independent from it. The imprecise and controversial definition of intelligence makes this comparison vague. Consciousness remains one of the main elements that AI seems to lack in order to imitate human intelligence. The question of comparison in fact raises ethical issues about the use, purpose and regulation of AI. â€œThe ways AI will change the future of workâ€ https://www.polytechnique-insights.com/en/columns/digital/artificial-intelligence-what-impact-will-it-have-on-work-in-the-future/ 75 million jobs could be automated Although the potential for change is much greater than automation, the risk remains very real, with 2.3% of jobs worldwide affected. Administrative jobs would be heavily impacted by automation. â€œCall centre employees, secretaries, data entry operators â€“ simple, linear activities with little variation in tasks and little interaction with others â€“ could be replaced by bots,â€ explains Janine Berg. In recent years, office workers have already seen their day-to-day work evolve. According to the experts, 24% of their tasks are highly exposed to AI, and 58% are moderately exposed. This is by far the occupation most at risk. This means that 2.3% of jobs worldwide, or 75 million, could end up being automated. The economist details a number of actions that governments need to take: â€œreflecting on the question of the balance of power, the voice of workers affected by labour market adjustments, respect for existing standards and rights, and the appropriate use of national social protections, as well as training systems will be crucial elements in steering the deployment of AI in the world of work.â€ Here are some videos also that touch on this subject https://www.ted.com/talks/richard_socher_why_ai_is_humanity_s_mirror_and_what_we_can_learn_from_it https://hbr.org/podcast/2024/02/the-science-of-making-truthful-ai?ab=HP-hero-latest-text-3 Interesting Paris-based project on / using AI https://www.telecom-paris.fr/en/research/strategic-focuses/data-science-artificial-intelligence Geopolitical implications of AI and digital surveillance adoption (touching on the case of China) https://www.brookings.edu/articles/geopolitical-implications-of-ai-and-digital-surveillance-adoption/ China vs. USA â€œtech raceâ€ â€” we can focus on this issue as it is very interesting https://www-ft-com.ezproxy.depaul.edu/content/ef157204-a204-4512-8c50-fe60e166b41e https://www.reuters.com/technology/china-aims-boost-chip-production-despite-us-restrictions-ft-2024-02-06/#:~:text=Feb%206%20(Reuters)%20%2D%20Chinese,Financial%20Times%20reported%20on%20Tuesday https://www.polytechnique-insights.com/en/braincamps/economy/the-technology-war-between-china-and-the-usa/china-and-the-race-for-technological-supremacy/ https://www.polytechnique-insights.com/en/braincamps/economy/the-technology-war-between-china-and-the-usa/semiconductors-at-the-heart-of-the-china-us-rivalry/ Europe overtakes US as biggest artificial intelligence research partner with China https://sciencebusiness.net/news-byte/ai/europe-overtakes-us-biggest-artificial-intelligence-research-partner-china Article about the Silicon Valley Bank crash that occurred last year https://www.techtarget.com/whatis/feature/Silicon-Valley-Bank-collapse-explained-What-you-need-to-know Articles recently about Elon Musk who is also utilising AI (he created a company called an AI company called xAI) https://edition.cnn.com/2024/01/30/investing/elon-musk-pay-package-thrown-out/index.html Musk vs. Chinese electric cars https://cleantechnica.com/2024/02/07/elon-musk-super-bullish-on-chinese-electric-car-companies/ Europe is getting more and more of these options, while the US is still basically barren when it comes to Chinese EV options.
